","about 1450":"omkring 1450","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1400–about 1450":"circa 1400–circa 1450","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1428–1520":"1428–1520","–Male":"Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1469":"1469","1400":"1400","1520":"1520","about 1400":"circa 1400","about 1422":"circa 1422","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"circa 1450","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1400–about 1450":"about 1400–about 1450","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1428–1520":"1428–1520","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1469":"1469","1400":"1400","1520":"1520","about 1400":"about 1400","about 1422":"about 1422","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"about 1450","Watford, Hertfordshire, England":"Watford, Hertfordshire, England","Doncaster, Yorkshire, England":"Doncaster, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Perrine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from the feminine form of   Perrin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","English: variant of   Perrin  . This surname is now rare in Britain and Ireland.","History: The surname <i>Perrine</i> of French origin (see 1 above) is listed along with its original form   Perrin   in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Perrin","meanings":["French and English: from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Perrin</i>, a pet form of Old French <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perine  ,   Perrine  , and   Prine  .","History: Henri Perrin from Louargat in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany (France), married Jeanne Merrin in Montreal, QC, in 1661. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variants or altered forms <i>Perrine</i> and <i>Pareyn</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. One of the Huguenot ancestors was Daniel Perrin (1642–1719), nicknamed <i>The Huguenot</i>, who arrived in New York in 1665, aboard the <i>Philip</i>, and settled first in NJ and later on Staten Island. Among his descendants the surname is common in the altered forms <i>Perrine</i>, <i>Perine</i> and <i>Prine</i>. The Staten Island community of Huguenot is named after Daniel Perrin and other Huguenots who settled in the area during the late 17th century."]}]},{"name":"Caroline","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the French form of Latin or Italian  <b>Carolina</b> , a feminine derivative of <i>Carolus</i> (  see  Charles  ). This name was used by certain gentry families from the 17th century onwards, no doubt in honour of the Stuart kings named <i>Charles</i>. It was famously borne by  Lady Caroline Lamb  (  1785–1828 ), mistress of the poet  Lord Byron ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carolyn","meanings":["Altered form of   Caroline ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Caroline Perrine was born about 1400, in Watford, Hertfordshire, England as the daughter of Sir David Perrine and Elizabeth Weedon. She married Sir Thomas John Abner Covert about 1422, in Doncaster, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1450, in her hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1400–about 1450":"umbes 1400–umbes 1450","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1400–1469":"1400–1469","1428–1520":"1428–1520","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1469":"1469","1400":"1400","1520":"1520","about 1400":"umbes 1400","about 1422":"umbes 1422","1450":"1450","1428":"1428","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Watford, Hertf